SIMPLE: clemency
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Clemency
<hw>Clem"en*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Clemencies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>clementia</ets>,
fr. <ets>clemens</ets> mild, calm.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Disposition
to forgive and spare, as offenders; mildness of temper; gentleness;
tenderness; mercy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Great <qex>clemency</qex> and tender zeal toward their
subjects.</q> <rj><qau>Stowe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They had applied for the royal <qex>clemency</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Mildness or softness of the elements; <as>as, the
<ex>clemency</ex> of the season</as>.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Mildness; tenderness; indulgence; lenity; mercy;
gentleness; compassion; kindness.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Clement</ent>⟦br⟧
